Prevention Program.
It is highly unlikely that the Worst Case Release Scenario or Alternative Release Scenarios will occur at the
plant for the following reasons:
The chlorine process and process areas are inspected daily;
The Plant is manned 24-hours per day, 7-days per week, 365-days per year;
The chlorine containers and storage rooms are monitored 24-hours per day, 7-days per week, 365-days per
year for process leaks via automatic leak detectors;
The leak detectors are considered critical equipment and thus are incorporated into the Mechanical Integrity
Program. As such, each detector is well maintained and tested twice each month;
An emergency chlorine scrubber has been installed (with building exhaust fans routed directly to the scrubber)
and is interlocked with the existing chlorine leak detectors and automatically starts operation when 3-ppm of
chlorine is detected by the leak detectors located within the chlorine storage and use areas;
The scrubber can also be manually activated in case of multiple failure of the chlorine leak detectors;
Maintenance of the scrubber (including exhaust fan, motor and scrubbing media quality) has been outsourced
to ensure continuous operation;
ALL chlorine storage, handling and use area entry doors are equipped with intruder alarms to guard against
unauthorized entry and/or vandalism;
ALL one ton containers are inspected prior to acceptance and storage onsite;
